Since you need **three** themes (not just light/dark), use the **ResourceDictionary swap** approach. `AppThemeBinding` only supports two themes, so it won't work here.

Here's the full setup:

## 1. Create three theme dictionaries with matching keys

**Themes/LightTheme.xaml**
```xml
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
                    x:Class="MyApp.Themes.LightTheme">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackgroundColor">White</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryTextColor">#333333</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#2196F3</Color>
    <Color x:Key="CardBackgroundColor">#F5F5F5</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

**Themes/DarkTheme.xaml**
```xml
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
                    x:Class="MyApp.Themes.DarkTheme">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackgroundColor">#121212</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryTextColor">#EEEEEE</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#BB86FC</Color>
    <Color x:Key="CardBackgroundColor">#1E1E1E</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

**Themes/HighContrastTheme.xaml**
```xml
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
                    x:Class="MyApp.Themes.HighContrastTheme">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackgroundColor">Black</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryTextColor">White</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">Yellow</Color>
    <Color x:Key="CardBackgroundColor">#1A1A1A</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

Each needs a code-behind:

```csharp
namespace MyApp.Themes;
public partial class LightTheme : ResourceDictionary
{
    public LightTheme() => InitializeComponent();
}
// Same pattern for DarkTheme and HighContrastTheme
```

> **Critical:** Every `x:Key` must exist in all three dictionaries. A missing key silently falls back to a default, causing inconsistent UI.

## 2. Use `DynamicResource` everywhere in your pages

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackgroundColor}">
    <Label Text="Welcome"
           TextColor="{DynamicResource PrimaryTextColor}" />
    <Button Text="Go"
            BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource AccentColor}" />
</ContentPage>
```

**Never use `StaticResource`** for themed keys — it freezes the value at load time and won't update on swap.

## 3. Build a theme service to swap and persist

```csharp
namespace MyApp.Services;

public class ThemeService
{
    const string ThemeKey = "AppTheme";

    public void ApplyTheme(string themeName)
    {
        ResourceDictionary theme = themeName switch
        {
            "Light"        => new Themes.LightTheme(),
            "Dark"         => new Themes.DarkTheme(),
            "HighContrast" => new Themes.HighContrastTheme(),
            _              => new Themes.LightTheme()
        };

        var merged = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;
        merged.Clear();
        merged.Add(theme);

        Preferences.Set(ThemeKey, themeName);
    }

    public void ApplySavedTheme()
    {
        var saved = Preferences.Get(ThemeKey, "Light");
        ApplyTheme(saved);
    }

    public string GetCurrentTheme() => Preferences.Get(ThemeKey, "Light");
}
```

## 4. Apply on startup in `App.xaml.cs`

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public App(ThemeService themeService)
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        themeService.ApplySavedTheme();
    }
}
```

Register it in `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<ThemeService>();
```

## 5. Settings page for user selection

```xml
<ContentPage x:Class="MyApp.SettingsPage"
             BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackgroundColor}">
    <VerticalStackLayout Padding="20" Spacing="10">
        <Label Text="Choose Theme"
               TextColor="{DynamicResource PrimaryTextColor}"
               FontSize="18" />
        <Picker x:Name="ThemePicker"
                SelectedIndexChanged="OnThemeChanged">
            <Picker.ItemsSource>
                <x:Array Type="{x:Type x:String}">
                    <x:String>Light</x:String>
                    <x:String>Dark</x:String>
                    <x:String>HighContrast</x:String>
                </x:Array>
            </Picker.ItemsSource>
        </Picker>
    </VerticalStackLayout>
</ContentPage>
```

```csharp
public partial class SettingsPage : ContentPage
{
    readonly ThemeService _themeService;

    public SettingsPage(ThemeService themeService)
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        _themeService = themeService;

        // Pre-select current theme
        ThemePicker.SelectedItem = _themeService.GetCurrentTheme();
    }

    void OnThemeChanged(object? sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        if (ThemePicker.SelectedItem is string theme)
            _themeService.ApplyTheme(theme);
    }
}
```

## 6. Android pitfall — don't forget `UiMode`

In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`, ensure `ConfigChanges.UiMode` is included:

```csharp
[Activity(Theme = "@style/Maui.SplashTheme", MainLauncher = true,
          ConfigurationChanges = ConfigChanges.ScreenSize
                               | ConfigChanges.Orientation
                               | ConfigChanges.UiMode
                               | ConfigChanges.ScreenLayout
                               | ConfigChanges.SmallestScreenSize
                               | ConfigChanges.Density)]
public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity { }
```

Without it, Android restarts the activity on system theme change — losing navigation state.

---

**Key takeaways:**
- **ResourceDictionary swap** is the only approach that supports 3+ themes
- All theme dictionaries must define the **exact same set of keys**
- Use **`DynamicResource`** (never `StaticResource`) for runtime updates
- Persist the user's choice with `Preferences` and reapply in the `App` constructor
